stehung des modernen Führungsgrundgebietes „Militärisches Nachrichtenwesen" auf. Die Präsentation ausgewählter Operationen zeigt, dass es dabei schon immer um mehr als nur Spionage ging, sondern um staatliches Wissensmanagement an den Schnittstellen von Militär, Polizei und Diplomatie.  aStates have been interested in gaining knowledge about their neighbors’ military potential since time immemorial. But it was only in the last third of the nineteenth century that they began creating organizations that worked in secret, gaining intelligence on an ongoing basis, analyzing it, and making it available to decision-makers. This book examines the founding history of military intelligence services between 1871 and 1914.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aErster Weltkrieg. 4aGeheimdienste. 4aMilitärgeschichte. 4aSpionage.  aFirst World War.  aespionage.  amilitary history.  asecret services.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1z97831113321920 cEPUBz97831113811380 cprintz978311138046940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311138094040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111380940423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111380940/original  a978-3-11-133219-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1b2024  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles